Question 1. Statistical learning Methods


(a) A flexible statistical learning method would be worse than an inflexible method, as n is small and so a flexible approach would overfit the small number of observations.
(b) A flexible statistical learning method would be better as n is large and a better fit would be reached due to the high number of observations.
(c) If the relationship is highly non-linear then a flexible statistical learning method is better. An inflexible method would not be suitable for a highly non-linear relationship.
(d) A flexible statistical learning method would be worse as it could closely follow the errors/fit the noise, compared to an inflexible method which would not.

Question 2. Bayes Rule


P(Play Golf = yes) = 10/20 = 0.5
P(Play Golf = no) = 10/20 = 0.5

P(Temperature = hot) = 12/20 = 0.6
P(Temperature = cool) = 8/20 = 0.4

P(Temperature = hot | Play Golf = yes) = 5/10 = 0.5
P(Temperature = cool | Play Golf = yes) = 5/10 = 0.5
P(Temperature = hot | Play Golf = no) = 7/10 = 0.7
P(Temperature = cool | Play Golf = no) = 3/10 = 0.3

According to Bayes rule:

P(Playing Golf = yes | Temperature = hot) = (0.5 * 0.5) / 0.6
* Answer = 0.417

P(Playing Golf = no | Temperature = hot) = (0.7 * 0.5) / 0.6
* Answer = 0.583

P(Playing Golf = yes | Temperature = cool) = (0.5 * 0.5) / 0.4
* Answer = 0.625

P(Playing Golf = no | Temperature = cool) = (0.3 * 0.5) / 0.4
* Answer = 0.375

Question 4. Linear regression


(a)

model_1 = lm(mpg ~ horsepower, data=Auto)
summary(model_1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ horsepower, data = Auto)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -13.5710  -3.2592  -0.3435   2.7630  16.9240 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 39.935861   0.717499   55.66   <2e-16 ***
## horsepower  -0.157845   0.006446  -24.49   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.906 on 390 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6059, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6049 
## F-statistic: 599.7 on 1 and 390 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

(i) Yes there is a relationship between mpg and horsepower. The p-value is extremely small: <2e-16. We can therefore reject a null hypothesis (generally we could reject a p-value below 0.05 if testing with 95% confidence). Our null hypothesis states that the slope is 0, i.e.that theres no relationship between mpg and horsepower. Now that its rejected we can say that there is a relationship.

(ii) The R2 value is nearly 0.6059 which tells us that in this regression model nearly 61% of the variance of mpg is explained by horsepower. This shows a relatively strong relationship, 100% being the strongest possible relationship and 0% being no relationship at all.

(iii) The relationship is negative. The estimate -0.157845 tells us that for every 1 unit increase in x (horsepower), there is an expected change of -0.157845 in y (mpg). This tells us that the relationship is negative.

As a side note, the F-statistic is very high and so leads us to again reject the null hypothesis; this again confirms that our results are statistically significant.

(iv)

predict(model_1, data.frame(horsepower=89), interval ="confidence", level = 0.99)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 25.88768 25.19633 26.57903
predict(model_1, data.frame(horsepower=89), interval="predict", level = 0.99)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 25.88768 13.17035 38.60501

The predicted mpg associated with a horsepower of 89 is 25.88768. The confidence interval is 25.19633 to 26.57903, meaning the range in which the true population parameter lies is small. The prediction interval is 13.1705 to 38.60501, which is a wider range than that of the confidence interval (which is expected).

The higher the AUROC value the better the model is at predicting classifiers (predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s). An optimal value would be 1 for TPR and 0 for FPR, therefore the best value we could achieve is 1. So the light model is the model that predicts the classes best (when compared with the CO2 and HumidityRatio models) as its AUROC value is the highest. The HumidityRatio is the poorest model at predicting the classes as it has the lowest AUROC value. In short, more area under the curve is better.

Question 6. Resampling methods


(a)
Model B (learns parameters for a polynomial degree 4) will fit the test data better. The data was generated from a polynomial of degree 3 and we have a good amount of training data (400 x,y-pairs), so the model for polynomial of degree 4 will likely fit a small coefficient for the 4th degree. This means that in actual fact it will act like a degree 3 (which our data was built from) so model B will fit the test data better. If we had less data pairs then polynomial degree 4 might overfit the data, however as we have 400 pairs overfitting is less likely and we want to avoid using model A is it would likely underfit the data.

(b)

set.seed(235)
x = 12 + rnorm(400)
y = 1 - x + 4*x^2 - 5*x^3 + rnorm(400)

plot(x, y)

The plot shows a linear relationship that is negative. The data is curved due to the cubic polynomial formula used to generate the data. There are no real outliers in the data and the data appears to be quite evenly distributed.

## [1] 115.8783

## [1] 130.9585

(ii). Second degree 4 model: LOOCV error

(ii). Second degree 4 model: 10-fold CV error

fold10_2_second = cv.glm(xy_data2, glm.fit2_second, K=10)
fold10_2_second$delta[1]
## [1] 0.9673976

The LOOCV error results are the same as in (c). The LOOCV errors are calculated by using the test error on every point, then taking the average of the errors - so you will get the same result every time as all possible splits are considered. However, for 10-fold CV errors the results differ from those in (c). This is because the approach involves randomly dividing the set of observations into 10 folds. This randomness means that you get a different result each time, as we can see here.

(e)
The smallest LOOCV error in (c) was seen in the (ii) degree 4 model.
The smallest 10-fold error in (c) was seen in the (ii) degree 4 model.
This is what I expected as I anticipdated that a model learnt from a polynomial of degree 4 would be more suitable to use on data generated from a polynomial of degree 3.

## 
## (Dispersion parameter for gaussian family taken to be 0.9436729)
## 
##     Null deviance: 1.7768e+09  on 399  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 3.7275e+02  on 395  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 1118.9
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 2

We see that the p-value for degree 4 is higher than degree 1,2 or 3 and so it is not statisically significant in comparison. Degree 1, 2 and 3 are all statistically significant. This is somewhat contradictory with our cross validation results which were lower for degree 4. However, strong predictivity does not necessarily mean strong significance, and vice versa, which is what we are seeing here. In the article entitled Why significant variables arent automatically good predictors by Lo, Chernoff, Zheng and Lo (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4653162/) the reasons for why higher significance cannot automatically imply stronger predictivity are discussed. This is effectively what we are seeing in our summary of glm.fit.2 and the corresonding cross-validation results. The coefficient estimates for degree 1, 2 and 3 are all negative and are extremely small numbers. This supports the very gradual negative curve seen in our plot. I will not comment on the degree 4 model is it is insignificant, although it is positve which does not agree with our plot (but therefore does agree with its statisical insignificance).

Here we can see that the LOOCV result for degree 4 is slightly lower. However, again the difference is very small. The overall very close similarities between both LOOCV and 10-fold CV values for degree 3 and degree 4 supports my statement that using degree 4 (Model B) will be very similar to degree 3, and therefore is the correct model to use (out of a choice between Model A and Model B in this question).
